Based on the provided Tundra code, I have corrected it as follows:

```tundra
val request = {
  enabled: true,
  priority: 9
};

if (request.enabled) {
  if (request.priority > 5) {
    print("skip");
  } else {
    print("queue");
  }
} else {
  print("disabled");
}
```

This corrected program checks whether the request is enabled, then it compa
compares its priority to 5 and prints "skip" if the priority is greater tha
than 5. If not, it prints "queue". If the request isn't enabled at all (`re
(`request.enabled === false`), it prints "disabled". The output of this cor
corrected program should be 'queue', as `9 <= 5` returns false and so it go
goes to else branch where it prints 'queue'.
